of retinal in each cone type"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe wavelength sensitivity of cone photoreceptors is determined by \u003Cstrong\u003Evariations in opsin protein structure\u003C/strong\u003E. Each cone type contains a specific opsin protein that, when bound to retinal, creates a photopigment with unique spectral sensitivity properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifferent numbers of membrane discs\u003C/strong\u003E - The number of membrane discs affects overall light sensitivity but does not influence which wavelengths of light the cone can detect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVarying amounts of calcium\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium plays an important role in the phototransduction cascade, it does not determine which wavelengths of light activate the photoreceptor.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifferent sizes of the outer segment\u003C/strong\u003E - The size of the outer segment influences the overall sensitivity to light but does not determine wavelength specificity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifferent concentrations of retinal\u003C/strong\u003E - All cone types use the same form of retinal molecule, and its concentration does not influence wavelength sensitivity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe three cone types (S, M, and L) each contain different opsins that create photopigments maximally sensitive to short (blue), medium (green), and long (red) wavelengths respectively. These differences in protein structure allow humans to discriminate between different wavelengths of light, forming the basis of colour vision.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The three types of cone photoreceptors contain different photopigments that are maximally sensitive to short (blue), medium (green), and long (red) wavelengths of light.","Each cone photopigment consists of opsin protein bound to retinal, with variations in the opsin structure determining wavelength sensitivity.","Normal colour vision requires all three cone types functioning properly."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:20:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:21:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"c